  "prompt": "Any good books to develop a statistical background? For a math major wanting to get more into stats",
  "response": "Absolutely! Here are some highly regarded books that can help you develop a strong statistical background:\n\n1. **\"Introduction to the Theory of Statistics\" by Alexander M. Mood, Franklin A. Graybill, and Duane C. Boes** \n   - This is a classic text that covers fundamental statistical theory.\n\n2. **\"Statistical Inference\" by George Casella and Roger L. Berger** \n   - This book is widely used in graduate courses and provides a thorough treatment of statistical theory.\n\n3. **\"All of Statistics: A Concise Course in Statistical Inference\" by Larry Wasserman** \n   - Larry Wasserman's book is excellent for a concise yet comprehensive overview of statistical inference.\n\n4. **\"Mathematical Statistics and Data Analysis\" by John A. Rice** \n   - This book is accessible and covers both theoretical and practical aspects of statistics.\n\n5. **\"Probability and Statistics\" by Morris H. DeGroot and Mark J. Schervish** \n   - An excellent choice that integrates probability theory with statistical methods.\n\n6. **\"The Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction\" by Trevor Hastie, Robert Tibshirani, and Jerome Friedman** \n   - This book is great for understanding statistical learning and its applications in data science.\n\n7. **\"Introduction to Probability\" by Dimitri P. Bertsekas and John N. Tsitsiklis** \n   - This book provides a solid foundation in probability, which is essential for understanding statistical methods.\n\n8. **\"Measure Theory and Probability Theory\" by Krishna B. Athreya and Soumendra N. Lahiri** \n   - For those looking for a deeper dive into the measure-theoretic foundations of probability and statistics.\n\n9. **\"Probability and Statistics for Engineers and Scientists\" by Ronald E. Walpole, Raymond H. Myers, Sharon L. Myers, and Keying E. Ye** \n   - While tailored for engineers and scientists, it is very accessible and covers a broad range of statistical topics.\n\n10. **\"Introduction to Statistical Learning with Applications in R\" by Gareth James, Daniela Witten, Trevor Hastie, and Robert Tibshirani** \n    - This book is particularly useful if you want to apply statistical methods using R.\n\nThese books should provide a strong foundation in both the theory and application of statistics, helping you bridge the gap from mathematics to statistical analysis.",
